WEBVTT

00:47.589 --> 00:49.966
- Are yous ready?
- Aye!

00:50.134 --> 00:53.845
On your marks! Get set!

00:54.012 --> 00:55.638
Go!

01:14.450 --> 01:16.325
Yeah!

01:21.206 --> 01:23.291
Stew, Dr Garrigan?

01:27.171 --> 01:29.630
And you, Dr Garrigan?

01:31.175 --> 01:35.094
- l, uh... I thought that...
- Mother.

01:35.262 --> 01:40.016
..seeing as we've something to celebrate,
we might have a wee drop.

01:40.184 --> 01:42.435
- Sherry, right. Great.
- Uh-huh.

01:42.603 --> 01:47.356
- We are very proud of you, Nicholas.
- Very proud.

01:47.524 --> 01:53.029
Not quite as good a degree as mine,
but a fine one nevertheless.

01:55.574 --> 02:01.746
Being a family doctor... Well, let me tell you,
Nicholas, you've chosen a fine life.

02:02.706 --> 02:05.750
lf you'll both raise your glasses...

02:05.918 --> 02:07.585
A toast.

02:07.753 --> 02:09.961
To father and son.

02:13.801 --> 02:16.302
A long future together.

02:35.614 --> 02:39.617
Nicholas, are you all right in there?

02:39.785 --> 02:45.623
l'm fine.

02:47.918 --> 02:51.003
OK, first place you land, you go.

02:51.171 --> 02:54.048
First place you land, you go.

02:57.594 --> 02:59.470
Canada.

04:05.120 --> 04:08.539
What are all the soldiers for?

04:08.707 --> 04:10.708
- Do you speak English?
- Yes.

04:10.876 --> 04:13.085
What are all the soldiers for?

04:13.253 --> 04:16.005
The army's taking over. There is a coup.

04:16.173 --> 04:19.091
- A coup? What? Are we safe?
- Don't worry.

04:19.259 --> 04:22.428
These are General Amin's men.
He fights for the people.

04:22.596 --> 04:25.139
- lt's a very happy day for us.
- OK.

04:41.406 --> 04:42.823
- ls that him?
- Yes.

04:44.409 --> 04:49.121
- What do you do in Scotland?
- Well, l'm a doctor, a qualified doctor.

04:50.082 --> 04:52.708
l thought I could maybe use my skills here.

04:56.463 --> 05:00.466
- Monkeys! Look. Look up there, Tolu.
- Do you have monkeys in Scotland?

05:00.634 --> 05:03.219
No, we don't have monkeys in Scotland.

05:03.929 --> 05:08.182
No. lf we had monkeys in Scotland,
we'd probably deep-fry them.

05:31.289 --> 05:34.125
This is my stop.

05:39.965 --> 05:42.883
l'm a medical officer overseas!

06:13.123 --> 06:14.457
Dr Garrigan!

06:16.793 --> 06:18.127
Uh, Dr Merrit?

06:18.295 --> 06:22.631
- No. l'm Sarah, David's wife. Welcome.
- Hello.

06:22.799 --> 06:26.218
- David was called out on an emergency.
- I hope everything's OK.

06:26.386 --> 06:29.180
Yeah, just normal business here.
Safe journey?

06:29.347 --> 06:31.974
Uh, well, you know. lt was...

06:32.142 --> 06:35.978
Bloody awful? A goat up your arse
and your face in someone's armpit.

06:36.146 --> 06:40.149
Last time I did that trip, I nearly asphyxiated.

06:40.317 --> 06:42.443
Right, hop in.

06:49.284 --> 06:53.120
- Actually, I waited for the bus yesterday.
- Oh, yeah?

06:53.288 --> 06:59.168
We were getting a little worried about you,
thought you might be caught up in the coup.

07:01.296 --> 07:05.091
lt's official now, by the way.
Obote's out. The radio's full of it.

07:05.258 --> 07:07.885
Who's Obote?

07:08.053 --> 07:11.680
- Ex-president.
- Oh, right. And whatshisname.

07:11.848 --> 07:14.433
Uh, Amin. He's taken over, yeah?

07:14.601 --> 07:17.228
You've certainly come at a busy time.

07:17.395 --> 07:20.481
Whatever I can do to help.

07:47.592 --> 07:49.677
- Morning, Nicholas.
- Morning.

07:49.845 --> 07:53.013
- So, what do you think?
- Aye, fine.

07:53.682 --> 07:55.391
Come on. Come through.

07:55.559 --> 07:59.895
This is the operating room.
Simple procedures for the most part.

08:00.063 --> 08:02.523
- Uh, morning.
- Morning.

08:04.693 --> 08:07.319
So, how many doctors are there here?

08:07.487 --> 08:10.614
Well, there's me and, uh, now there's you.

08:10.782 --> 08:13.409
- Morning, Sister.
- Morning.

08:13.577 --> 08:16.704
You know, the interesting thing is,

08:16.872 --> 08:21.458
80% of the locals
still prefer the witch doctor to us.

08:21.626 --> 08:26.881
Sometimes I think we're just
skimming the surface of an ocean.

08:27.924 --> 08:29.758
- Ready?
- Yeah.

08:29.926 --> 08:32.428
There we are.

08:32.636 --> 08:35.097
There we go. Yeah.

08:35.265 --> 08:36.932
OK.

08:38.268 --> 08:39.934
Yes, thank you.

08:41.270 --> 08:44.648
OK, and one more. OK, who's next?

08:44.816 --> 08:47.484
That's a lovely name. OK. Can I see?

09:08.298 --> 09:11.217
You ready? Now, come on, Angela.

09:53.426 --> 09:56.178
Dr Merrit.

09:58.723 --> 10:00.599
What is it?

10:00.767 --> 10:03.936
- Complications with the Mugisha baby.
- I'll go.

10:04.104 --> 10:06.939
No, no. I better go. I know the mother.

10:07.983 --> 10:10.067
Sorry.

10:10.235 --> 10:12.695
l'll be back in an hour or two.

10:14.155 --> 10:16.699
Bonny.

10:16.866 --> 10:18.909
- Jump in.
- Hi, Bonny.

10:19.077 --> 10:21.161
Hi.

10:32.882 --> 10:36.135
- I hope you don't mind me saying this, but...
- Yeah?

10:36.303 --> 10:40.848
You seem an unlikely candidate
for this kind of work.

10:41.933 --> 10:44.643
Why? Cos I don't wear socks and sandals?

10:44.811 --> 10:46.645
TouchÃ©.

10:46.813 --> 10:49.481
l still want to make a difference, you know.

10:49.649 --> 10:51.900
- Really?
- Yes, really.

10:52.068 --> 10:57.406
l wanna have fun, too, though.
A bit of adventure, something different.

10:57.574 --> 10:59.408
That's a lot of things.

10:59.576 --> 11:01.535
ls it?

11:09.961 --> 11:11.170
Doctor!

11:21.848 --> 11:23.932
Yeah!

11:26.394 --> 11:29.188
A beautiful goal for Scotland!

11:30.565 --> 11:32.024
Yeah!

11:34.361 --> 11:37.029
- A good one.
- Bonny, why are the women singing?

11:37.197 --> 11:40.699
You don't know?
The president is coming to the village.

11:42.035 --> 11:44.453
Where's Dr Merrit?

11:44.621 --> 11:48.165
- He has gone to town for stores.
- OK.

11:48.333 --> 11:52.795
Come on. I thought you might be
slightly curious to see the new boss.

11:52.962 --> 11:55.964
l don't work for Amin.

11:56.132 --> 11:57.883
Right. Fine.

11:58.051 --> 12:00.928
l just thought it might be... fun.

12:04.474 --> 12:06.308
OK.

12:07.268 --> 12:09.436
OK, OK.

12:25.245 --> 12:28.497
Amin! Amin!

13:01.072 --> 13:03.740
Uganda! Oh, yeah!

13:05.285 --> 13:07.035
Oh, yeah!

13:07.203 --> 13:10.914
Uganda! Oh, yeah!
Uganda! Oh, yeah!

13:17.755 --> 13:20.924
And I want to promise you

13:21.092 --> 13:25.804
this will be a government
of action, not of words.

13:30.143 --> 13:33.395
We will build new schools,

13:33.563 --> 13:35.898
new roads...

13:36.941 --> 13:40.027
and new houses!

13:41.696 --> 13:44.156
l may wear

13:44.324 --> 13:47.534
the uniform of a general...

13:48.703 --> 13:51.663
but, uh...

13:51.831 --> 13:55.250
..in my heart, I am a simple man

13:55.418 --> 13:57.461
like you.

13:58.505 --> 14:03.509
l know who you are
and everything that you are.

14:04.010 --> 14:05.677
l am you.

14:07.055 --> 14:09.056
Ask my soldiers.

14:09.224 --> 14:14.937
All my life, I never eat food
until my soldiers have eaten first.

14:18.399 --> 14:21.818
lt will be like this in Uganda now.

14:21.986 --> 14:26.156
Together, we will make this country better.

14:29.786 --> 14:31.703
And stronger!

14:33.122 --> 14:35.832
And free!

14:39.420 --> 14:47.553
Uganda! Oh, yeah!

14:49.889 --> 14:52.224
- Have you seen enough now?
- What?

14:52.392 --> 14:55.143
Have you seen enough now?

14:55.311 --> 14:57.437
Just a couple of minutes.

15:08.366 --> 15:10.826
- Can we please go now?
- OK.

15:14.581 --> 15:16.415
Uganda!

15:25.300 --> 15:28.385
They sang just like that for Obote...

15:28.553 --> 15:32.264
until they realised he turned their economy
into his bank account.

15:32.432 --> 15:36.059
- Come on. Give the man a chance.
- l'm serious.

15:36.227 --> 15:38.687
You talk to me in a couple of years.

15:44.360 --> 15:47.571
What's going on?

15:49.532 --> 15:51.033
Jesus.

15:54.871 --> 15:56.705
What's the problem?

15:56.873 --> 15:58.081
They need a doctor.

16:00.793 --> 16:05.589
- The president's been hurt in an accident.
- We have to come. We'll follow you.

16:05.757 --> 16:07.591
God. Terrifying.

16:20.688 --> 16:22.981
My hand!

16:23.149 --> 16:26.485
My hand is broken!

16:26.653 --> 16:29.363
Get that farmer out of my sight!

16:35.953 --> 16:37.537
Hey. Hey.

16:40.750 --> 16:42.959
Come. Come here.

16:44.921 --> 16:50.801
l'm Dr Garrigan. I hear you have a problem
with your hand. l'd like to examine it.

16:55.264 --> 16:58.392
There you go.
Could you just raise your thumb like that?

17:00.353 --> 17:03.522
- How's that? ls that OK?
- Yeah. Uh-huh.

17:03.690 --> 17:08.359
Sarah, I think we're gonna need a splint. Can
somebody do something about that cow?

17:08.528 --> 17:12.698
Um, I don't think you've broken it.
l think it's just sprained.

17:12.865 --> 17:14.866
Please, it's in pain!

17:26.796 --> 17:29.840
Can you hold that there
with your other hand, please?

17:30.007 --> 17:35.387
Sarah, can you go and talk to that farmer
about his cow, please?

17:46.941 --> 17:50.277
Sarah, how's it going?

17:58.035 --> 18:02.330
- Somebody put that animal out of its misery!
- I am trying to explain to them.

18:02.498 --> 18:03.957
For God's sake!

18:26.898 --> 18:28.690
l'm sorry. l...

18:30.651 --> 18:33.904
- I couldn't hear myself think.
- You took my gun.

18:34.071 --> 18:35.447
- Yeah.
- Who are you?

18:35.615 --> 18:40.118
Nicholas G... l'm Dr Nicholas Garrigan.
l work at the medical compound in Mogambo.

18:40.286 --> 18:42.829
- l'm a... l'm a doctor.
- You are British?

18:42.997 --> 18:45.874
Brit... Uh, well, l'm Scottish.

18:46.042 --> 18:47.959
l'm Scottish.

18:48.127 --> 18:50.420
- Scottish.
- Yeah.

18:50.588 --> 18:54.132
Why didn't you say so?
l fought with the Scots against the Mau Mau.

18:54.300 --> 18:57.886
Great soldiers. Very brave.
And good people, completely.

18:58.054 --> 19:03.433
Let me tell you, if I could be anything
instead of a Ugandan, I would be a Scot.

19:03.601 --> 19:05.143
Right. Really?

19:05.311 --> 19:10.816
Except for the... the red hair,
which I am sure is attractive to your women,

19:10.983 --> 19:14.986
but which we Africans,
we find this quite disgusting.

19:16.864 --> 19:21.034
Thank you, Dr Garrigan. A very good job.

19:22.495 --> 19:23.578
Hey.

19:23.746 --> 19:25.288
Please.

19:25.456 --> 19:30.126
Would you let me have this T-shirt?
My son Campbell, he would love this T-shirt.

19:30.294 --> 19:33.797
- You've got a son called Campbell?
- Yeah.

19:33.965 --> 19:38.134
Maybe you would take my shirt here
in exchange.

19:38.302 --> 19:41.054
Right. Of course. Yeah.

19:45.393 --> 19:47.519
Ah!

19:47.687 --> 19:49.437
Thank you.

19:49.605 --> 19:50.689
Uh-huh.

19:50.857 --> 19:54.109
You see? Now you are a general like me.

19:54.277 --> 19:56.403
Salute, please.

19:58.865 --> 20:02.951
Now I must leave.

20:24.932 --> 20:27.350
l bet you that's worth a few bob.

20:27.518 --> 20:29.561
Yeah.

20:34.275 --> 20:37.485
l still can't believe how you shot that cow.

20:38.529 --> 20:40.614
You're mad.

20:43.075 --> 20:44.826
Um, anyway, l...

20:44.994 --> 20:48.413
Do you fancy a wee drink on the porch?

20:48.581 --> 20:50.832
No, thank you. l'm OK, really.

20:51.000 --> 20:53.877
l... Nicholas, I have to go.

20:55.588 --> 20:59.716
Look, it's fine, all right?
We're just having a drink.

21:06.265 --> 21:08.475
Oh, God.

21:08.643 --> 21:10.769
l can't do this.

21:10.937 --> 21:13.104
What?

21:13.272 --> 21:15.982
My husband is a good man.

21:16.150 --> 21:18.860
Oh, Christ. I sound ridiculous.

21:22.156 --> 21:25.700
l guess... I guess I just need you
to understand why l'm here.

21:25.868 --> 21:29.454
- lt's OK. I do understand.
- No, you don't.

21:30.998 --> 21:33.583
- l'm sorry.
- lt's OK.

21:33.751 --> 21:36.419
lt's just sometimes...

21:36.587 --> 21:40.507
when you're married to
such a very good man...

21:42.051 --> 21:45.804
it's... it makes you feel...

21:45.972 --> 21:47.639
Like shit.

21:49.934 --> 21:52.435
My father's the same.

21:55.106 --> 21:57.649
And...

21:57.817 --> 22:00.527
it's nice to be noticed.

22:03.948 --> 22:06.282
- Oh, I can't. I can't.
- Sarah, it's...

22:06.450 --> 22:08.994
- l'm sorry. l'm sorry.
- lt's fine.

22:10.329 --> 22:12.455
- No, don't, please.
- Sarah, it's fine.

22:12.623 --> 22:14.457
Please.

22:40.359 --> 22:42.360
Nicholas!

22:43.863 --> 22:47.699
Nicholas, there are some people
here to see you.

22:47.867 --> 22:51.494
l'll be, um, right there, David.

22:51.662 --> 22:53.705
Right. Right.

22:57.835 --> 22:59.878
- Good morning, Dr Garrigan.
- Morning.

23:00.046 --> 23:02.839
My name is Jonah Wasswa,
Minister of Health.

23:03.007 --> 23:06.176
l've been sent by
his Excellency President Amin.

23:06.343 --> 23:09.888
- There is something he would like to ask you.
- What?

23:10.056 --> 23:11.931
Sarah?

23:12.892 --> 23:17.687
Oh, hey. Listen, why don't you tell David
to rearrange the field trip for Friday?

23:17.855 --> 23:21.566
l'll be back as soon as I can. He probably
just wants me to retie his bandages.

23:21.734 --> 23:24.402
See you later.

23:33.329 --> 23:37.499
- My name is Masanga.
- Nice to meet you. l'm Nicholas.

23:37.666 --> 23:42.879
Pleased to meet you, Mr Nicholas.
Welcome to the president's car.

23:48.302 --> 23:50.720
- They think you are the president.
- Eh?

23:50.888 --> 23:53.765
They think you are the president.

24:18.457 --> 24:21.918
* Love you, love you, baby

24:22.086 --> 24:24.462
* You give me fever

24:26.841 --> 24:30.051
* Love you, love you, darling

24:30.219 --> 24:32.929
* Cos you give me fever

24:35.141 --> 24:36.975
* I love the way you walk

24:37.143 --> 24:39.394
* I love the way you talk

24:39.562 --> 24:41.437
* I love the way you move

24:41.605 --> 24:43.606
* Love the way you groove

24:43.774 --> 24:46.442
* Love you, love you, baby

24:47.486 --> 24:49.445
* Because you give me

24:49.613 --> 24:52.115
* Give me fever

24:52.283 --> 24:53.700
* Give me

24:53.868 --> 24:56.661
* Give me fever

24:56.829 --> 24:58.872
The president's house.

25:03.335 --> 25:05.628
Please, sit down.

25:05.796 --> 25:09.340
- His Excellency will be with you in a moment.
- Who's this?

25:09.508 --> 25:13.344
- Uh, Dr Junju. The previous incumbent.
- Of what?

25:13.512 --> 25:19.434
Of the post...
of personal physician to the president.

25:19.602 --> 25:24.022
Hold on to your guns, everyone!
Hold on to your guns!

25:27.526 --> 25:30.820
Good to see you again, Dr Garrigan.
You see, Jonah?

25:30.988 --> 25:37.202
This is the sort of man a president needs,
someone who is not afraid to speak his mind.

25:38.245 --> 25:42.290
So, what do you say, Nicholas?
Will you take the job?

25:43.209 --> 25:46.753
l'm sorry, um...
you want me to be your physician?

25:46.921 --> 25:49.005
Mm.

25:49.173 --> 25:53.885
- Do you want to be of service to Uganda?
- Yes, I do.

25:54.053 --> 25:59.557
Then what better way
than to look after the health of its president?

25:59.725 --> 26:02.727
Let me tell you, it will not be a difficult job

26:02.895 --> 26:08.900
because me, myself,
l am a man in perfect physical condition.

26:09.068 --> 26:13.571
Also, I know precisely when I will die.

26:13.739 --> 26:16.366
lt came to me in a dream.

26:16.533 --> 26:20.745
So you do not have to worry
about making a mistake.

26:22.248 --> 26:24.916
l'm really sorry. l'm very honoured, but...

26:25.084 --> 26:27.627
Nicholas, I understand.

26:28.671 --> 26:31.798
Me, myself, I did not want to be president,

26:31.966 --> 26:35.260
but the people, they wanted it so.

26:35.427 --> 26:39.430
Listen to me. This is very important.

26:39.598 --> 26:42.016
Here, in Kampala,

26:42.184 --> 26:47.438
you will have a hand in creating
a new health service for this country,

26:47.606 --> 26:51.484
something that will help millions of people.

26:52.611 --> 26:55.947
l'm sorry. I do have a commitment
to the mission in Mogambo

26:56.115 --> 26:59.284
and l'd be letting them down horribly.
You see?

27:06.709 --> 27:08.251
Uh!

27:09.295 --> 27:13.589
lt's the woman, the one I saw you with.
You want to get back to be with her.

27:13.757 --> 27:17.135
Well, not entirely.

27:17.303 --> 27:20.138
lt's the woman. lt's the woman.

27:20.306 --> 27:24.475
Why don't you tell her
to come and be here with us?

27:24.643 --> 27:27.061
lt's not that simple. lt's complicated.

27:27.229 --> 27:29.564
Why?

27:29.732 --> 27:31.983
ls she married?

27:32.151 --> 27:34.193
Yes, she is.

27:36.822 --> 27:38.281
Doctor!

27:38.449 --> 27:41.367
Doctor, you, you are very naughty.

27:41.535 --> 27:43.036
Me?

27:44.830 --> 27:47.832
Ah, now you are even more interesting.

27:48.000 --> 27:53.296
Married woman...
they are always the most passionate, huh?

27:55.174 --> 27:58.217
- lt's true.
- They are so grateful, huh?

28:01.889 --> 28:03.848
Hm. Yes.

28:05.517 --> 28:08.186
l'm sorry. l'm sorry for wasting your time.

28:08.354 --> 28:09.979
No, no.

28:10.147 --> 28:13.941
My car will take you back
first thing in the morning.

28:14.109 --> 28:19.280
But... in the meantime,
tonight we are having a state dinner.

28:19.448 --> 28:24.118
- Please, would you join us there?
- l'd very much like that. Thank you.

28:24.286 --> 28:26.704
You have a suit? A dark suit?

28:26.872 --> 28:29.540
- No. No, I don't.
- Hm...

28:41.804 --> 28:45.390
How much is this gonna cost me, by the way?

28:45.557 --> 28:48.518
lt's OK. lt's on president's account.

28:49.436 --> 28:52.021
- Can I just...
- Hey!

28:52.189 --> 28:53.648
Stop! Hey!

29:01.407 --> 29:06.077
- What's going on?
- Obote's men. They're everywhere.

29:06.245 --> 29:08.454
- Really?
- Yep.

29:08.622 --> 29:11.249
They're communists, you know?

29:11.417 --> 29:14.335
Mind you, Amin's more than
a match for them.

29:14.503 --> 29:17.255
He's ex-British army. King's African Rifles.

29:17.423 --> 29:21.050
Jamshid, pack those up
and have them sent to the High Commission.

29:21.218 --> 29:22.844
OK, thank you.

29:23.011 --> 29:27.849
Yes, he's a little unpredictable,
but he's got a firm hand.

29:28.016 --> 29:33.354
Only thing the African
really understands. Thanks, Jamshid.

29:37.651 --> 29:41.571
Yeah, up yours, too, pal.
Bloody English.

30:03.969 --> 30:06.053
Oh, hello.

30:12.895 --> 30:14.896
Hello.

30:19.276 --> 30:24.489
- Hello there. How do you do?
- Ah, Nicholas! l'm so happy you came.

30:24.656 --> 30:26.824
- So am l.
- Please. Please, this way.

30:26.992 --> 30:29.660
l want to introduce you
to my wives. Excuse me.

30:29.828 --> 30:34.457
This is Malyamu. She is my first wife.
She has given me five children.

30:34.625 --> 30:36.167
Uh, hello.

30:36.335 --> 30:39.504
And this one... Nora. She has given me three.

30:39.671 --> 30:41.172
Hi there.

30:41.340 --> 30:44.050
And that here is Kay.

30:44.218 --> 30:47.303
- Yes. This is Dr Nicholas Garrigan.
- Hello.

30:47.471 --> 30:51.807
- He saved my life.
- Really, I just stitched his hand up.

30:51.975 --> 30:55.478
- Don't be so modest.
- lt is you I have to thank for the T-shirt.

30:55.646 --> 30:58.773
Oh, right. So you must be
Campbell's mother?

30:58.941 --> 31:01.776
- Yes.
- lt's a pleasure meeting you.

31:01.944 --> 31:04.695
Come. I have to introduce you
to some people.

31:07.574 --> 31:08.699
Excuse me.

31:08.867 --> 31:12.703
This is British High Commissioner
Mr Perkins.

31:12.871 --> 31:16.791
- How do you do?
- Meet my good friend Dr Nicholas Garrigan.

31:16.959 --> 31:19.544
- And his colleague Mr Stone.
- How do you do?

31:19.711 --> 31:22.213
Uh, yes, we've already met.

31:22.381 --> 31:24.966
- Ah. I will talk with you later.
- Oh, right.

31:25.133 --> 31:28.886
So, uh, Dr Garrigan. We've been hearing
all sorts of things about you.

31:29.054 --> 31:32.640
Yes, l, uh... I gather the president
has clasped you to his bosom.

31:32.808 --> 31:34.892
Uh, no, no. Not exactly.

31:35.060 --> 31:37.186
What do you make of him?

31:37.354 --> 31:39.897
l think he's doing
rather a great job. Don't you?

31:40.065 --> 31:44.819
Yes. There's issues to be sorted out,
but, no, he plays a pretty straight bat.

31:44.987 --> 31:47.154
Yes, definitely one of us.

31:47.322 --> 31:51.033
Anyway, it's very good
to have another Englishman around.

31:51.201 --> 31:53.244
- Scot.
- What?

31:53.412 --> 31:56.789
l'm a Scotsman.

31:59.042 --> 32:01.586
Ladies and gentlemen.

32:01.753 --> 32:06.257
Friends, I am speaking with you now
because if I wait until later,

32:06.425 --> 32:09.427
you will be too drunk to hear my voice.

32:11.597 --> 32:14.849
Here is where civilisation began.

32:15.684 --> 32:17.643
Here in Africa.

32:17.811 --> 32:22.732
Here is where the Greeks
stole their philosophy

32:22.899 --> 32:26.110
and the Arabs took their medicine.

32:26.278 --> 32:30.781
We Ugandans
must be more proud of this history.

32:30.949 --> 32:35.536
We are an independent African nation,

32:35.704 --> 32:40.541
living in peace and economic power.

32:41.001 --> 32:43.252
- Black power.
- Yes.

32:44.004 --> 32:49.050
Just like all you people
thought would never be possible.

32:51.511 --> 32:53.804
And now we will go through to dinner.

32:53.972 --> 32:56.974
The food tonight, it is all local,

32:57.142 --> 32:59.477
special food.

32:59.645 --> 33:01.979
And none of it is human flesh.

33:04.107 --> 33:06.609
This is my last.

33:17.287 --> 33:20.831
Dr Garrigan, please come quickly.
The president is very sick.

33:22.668 --> 33:26.962
They have poisoned me.
They are trying to assassinate me!

33:27.130 --> 33:28.756
Nicholas.

33:29.758 --> 33:33.260
I just have to examine your stomach.

33:34.221 --> 33:37.515
Obote's people are everywhere.
They want me dead, Nicholas.

33:37.683 --> 33:41.060
OK, I just... I need to do this. OK?

33:42.187 --> 33:44.522
One more, one more.

33:44.690 --> 33:47.108
OK. OK. OK.

33:51.405 --> 33:56.075
OK, I think I know what this is.
Let me listen, just listen.

34:00.122 --> 34:03.958
OK. Yeah. OK.
l think I know what this is. Bear with me.

34:04.126 --> 34:06.043
Uh...

34:15.262 --> 34:17.847
There we are. OK?

34:18.014 --> 34:22.016
l'm gonna ask you
to sit on this pouf right here.

34:25.813 --> 34:28.565
What is this? What is this?

34:28.734 --> 34:33.027
l'll just hold it against your stomach.
l'll ask you to stand up in three.

34:33.196 --> 34:36.741
One, two, three. Go.

34:57.137 --> 34:59.597
l feel better, much better!

35:03.727 --> 35:07.396
Yes, you are a good doctor. Thank you.

35:07.564 --> 35:11.358
ln future, remember
not to mix beer with aspirin.

35:13.820 --> 35:17.656
- That was the cause?
- I think so. Yes.

35:18.658 --> 35:21.744
l am ashamed that you saw me like that.

35:21.912 --> 35:24.830
l was frightened.

35:24.998 --> 35:28.959
l'm a doctor. Everything that passes
between us is confidential.

35:29.127 --> 35:31.837
OK? l've taken an oath.

35:32.005 --> 35:34.965
But a man who shows fear,

35:35.133 --> 35:38.803
he is weak and he is a slave.

35:40.096 --> 35:44.892
Well, if you're afraid of dying,
it shows you have a life worth keeping.

35:50.565 --> 35:54.610
You see? You are a doctor...

35:54.778 --> 35:58.113
and also a philosopher.

35:58.281 --> 36:01.992
Yes. I do have a good life now.

36:03.036 --> 36:05.412
Please. Please, sit.

36:05.580 --> 36:07.414
Sit here.

36:11.878 --> 36:15.589
l come from a very poor family.

36:15.757 --> 36:20.678
l think you should know this.
My father, he left me when I was a child.

36:20.846 --> 36:24.473
The British army, it became my home.

36:24.641 --> 36:27.309
They took me as a...

36:27.477 --> 36:29.979
cleaner in the kitchen,

36:30.146 --> 36:32.481
cleaning pots.

36:32.649 --> 36:34.859
They used to beat me.

36:36.403 --> 36:38.821
"Build this wall, Amin."

36:38.989 --> 36:41.490
"Dig this latrine, Amin."

36:41.658 --> 36:44.034
And now, here I am,

36:44.202 --> 36:46.745
the President of Uganda.

36:47.831 --> 36:50.416
And who put me here? Eh?

36:52.627 --> 36:54.962
lt was the British.

36:57.757 --> 37:00.050
What a story.

37:02.262 --> 37:05.931
- Good night, Nicholas.
- Good night, sir.

37:21.531 --> 37:25.034
- Uh, hello. Sarah, it's Nicholas.
- Nicholas, where are you?

37:25.201 --> 37:27.244
I'm still in Kampala, actually.

37:27.412 --> 37:29.413
Thank you.

37:29.581 --> 37:35.252
Look, the president's offered me a job here.
Normally, I wouldn't even consider it, but...

37:35.420 --> 37:38.255
under the circumstances...

37:38.423 --> 37:41.216
l thought it might be quite a good idea.

37:43.303 --> 37:45.596
l... I see.

37:46.056 --> 37:51.268
- David will be disappointed.
- Well, I'll write to David, of course I will.

37:51.436 --> 37:53.270
Of course.

37:53.438 --> 37:57.733
l just hope you can do as much good there
as you could've done here.

37:57.901 --> 38:02.363
Look, somebody's calling me. l'd better go.

38:02.530 --> 38:03.989
Sure.

38:04.157 --> 38:07.952
All right. Well, listen, bye, Sarah.
l'll be in touch.

38:08.119 --> 38:09.328
Bye.

38:25.971 --> 38:32.226
When you're not treating the president or his
family, the hospital could use your expertise.

38:36.690 --> 38:40.275
This is one of our new medical wards.

38:43.113 --> 38:48.492
Further down the corridor are the operating
theatres, which the president has paid for.

38:48.660 --> 38:51.328
- Yes, sir.
- Hi, Doctor.

38:51.496 --> 38:53.998
Welcome to Mulago. Dr...?

38:54.165 --> 38:56.250
Garrigan. Hello.

38:56.418 --> 39:01.255
l do hope you find the hospital
up to the standard you're used to.

39:03.383 --> 39:06.468
Uh, excuse me. Who was that?

39:06.636 --> 39:09.847
Your predecessor Dr Junju.

39:10.015 --> 39:12.349
- Never mind him.
- Excuse me, sir.

39:12.517 --> 39:14.852
He's here.

39:15.020 --> 39:17.771
- Excuse me a moment.
- Of course.

39:20.275 --> 39:23.569
- Hello.
- Jolly nice to meet you.

39:30.452 --> 39:32.870
Dr Garrigan.

39:33.747 --> 39:38.500
Just topping up on quinine.
So, you decided to stay?

39:38.668 --> 39:40.878
- Uh, yes. Yes, I did.
- Yeah, excellent.

39:41.046 --> 39:45.883
Listen, I just wanted to say that if there's
anything we can possibly help you with,

39:46.051 --> 39:49.178
please don't hesitate.

39:49.345 --> 39:53.057
What? You're my new best friend now?

39:54.100 --> 39:56.602
Do just stay in touch.

39:56.770 --> 39:58.520
Why?

39:58.688 --> 40:01.482
Well, given that we were so, um...

40:02.901 --> 40:07.738
intimately involved
with the President coming to power,

40:07.906 --> 40:11.700
the foreign office has asked me
to point out our awareness

40:11.868 --> 40:17.456
of your very unique personal relationship
with President Amin.

40:19.375 --> 40:25.756
Should you find the need to clarify your
status regarding details of that relationship,

40:25.924 --> 40:31.929
we would of course welcome any clarification
you might feel the need to share with us.

40:35.517 --> 40:40.729
ls there some special school
where you people learn to talk that bollocks?

40:43.817 --> 40:46.902
Do, please, stay in touch.

40:47.946 --> 40:50.614
You... you take care now.

40:58.248 --> 41:00.749
This man is going to kill the president.

41:00.917 --> 41:05.462
So Nicholas walks up to that cow
and he shoots it in the head.

41:06.548 --> 41:09.883
On your marks! Get set!

41:11.469 --> 41:13.220
Go!

41:13.388 --> 41:16.849
Amin! Amin!

41:22.021 --> 41:24.314
l won.

41:36.494 --> 41:39.079
- OK. Here, Nicholas.
- Oh, no, no, no.

41:44.586 --> 41:49.506
- Before I forget... I need to ask a favour.
- Anything.

41:49.674 --> 41:54.761
l will be in Libya next week, and I need you
to attend a meeting in my place.

41:54.929 --> 42:00.642
- What kind of meeting?
- A simple matter of taste and common sense.

42:00.810 --> 42:03.395
l cannot think of anyone better than you.

42:16.159 --> 42:21.371
Ah, gentlemen. Please, don't get up.
The president sends his apologies.

42:21.539 --> 42:27.211
He's been called away at short notice
and he's asked me to step in.

42:27.712 --> 42:32.299
- And you are?
- Nicholas Garrigan. His doctor.

42:32.884 --> 42:35.093
- His doctor?
- Yes.

42:36.137 --> 42:39.556
- And you are?
- l'm the Austrian foreign minister.

42:39.724 --> 42:42.559
This is Dr Rommel,
one of our leading architects,

42:42.727 --> 42:46.146
and Dr Bruner
from the institute of civil engineering.

42:46.314 --> 42:49.274
Together, we are the first bid.

42:49.442 --> 42:51.526
Bid, right.

42:52.528 --> 42:54.071
For what, precisely?

43:03.581 --> 43:06.333
l love it!

43:06.501 --> 43:09.920
Good choice. Modern, elegant.

43:10.088 --> 43:12.422
A symbol of Uganda's future.

43:12.590 --> 43:16.051
Here is where we will have
the next Pan-African Congress.

43:16.219 --> 43:20.055
- Nice.
- My two closest advisers.

43:20.223 --> 43:23.183
Tweedledum and Tweedledee.

43:25.561 --> 43:28.563
- Look what Nicholas has designed for me.
- Nice.

43:28.731 --> 43:31.692
- Well, I didn't design anything. lt was...
- Nonsense.

43:31.859 --> 43:34.444
You have a wonderful eye.

43:34.612 --> 43:38.073
Jonah... he has no taste.

43:38.241 --> 43:40.325
Look at him.

43:40.493 --> 43:42.786
Even his suits, they look silly.

43:42.954 --> 43:45.205
ls that not right, Jonah?

43:54.674 --> 44:00.554
- What is it you want, Jonah?
- I have ministerial papers for your signature.

44:00.722 --> 44:03.765
Go. I will sign them later.

44:12.692 --> 44:15.902
l do not like the way that man looks at me.

44:16.946 --> 44:20.490
- Do you think he looks at me strangely?
- No.

44:20.658 --> 44:23.201
No, I can't say that l've noticed.

44:24.120 --> 44:26.496
OK, enlargement of the mediastinum

44:26.664 --> 44:30.751
and reticulonodular lung patterns
all indicating pulmonary TB.

44:30.918 --> 44:34.171
Yeah, but it could be...

44:35.298 --> 44:37.382
What was that?

44:55.276 --> 44:59.029
Makindye prison,
where Obote's people are being held.

45:01.199 --> 45:03.367
Can you hear that?

45:04.410 --> 45:07.287
Dr Garrigan! Dr Garrigan!

45:07.455 --> 45:11.041
Please come quickly.
The president's son is sick.

45:12.126 --> 45:16.505
What's wrong with him?
What's wrong with him, huh?

45:21.302 --> 45:25.430
Can you hear me, child?
l'm begging you to stop it, Mackenzie!

45:25.598 --> 45:29.518
- OK. Thank you. You can step away.
- Stop it, Mackenzie, please!

45:29.685 --> 45:31.937
- Hi. Your son's epileptic?
- I don't know.

45:32.105 --> 45:34.815
- What? Has he been like this before, then?
- Yes.

45:34.982 --> 45:39.945
Right, OK. Can you hold his knees up
against his chest? The other hand back here.

45:40.113 --> 45:42.572
- This is Campbell?
- This is Mackenzie.

45:42.740 --> 45:45.075
Mackenzie. Right.

45:45.243 --> 45:48.370
Mackenzie, I am Dr Garrigan, OK?

45:48.538 --> 45:51.373
We're gonna sort you out.
We'll get you to hospital.

45:51.541 --> 45:55.877
No, no. The president will not allow it.
You must do what you can do from here.

45:56.045 --> 45:58.755
- The child has to go to hospital.
- Please!

45:59.882 --> 46:01.675
Please.

46:02.677 --> 46:05.262
lt's OK. Mamma's here.

46:05.972 --> 46:09.599
Mamma's here. lt's OK. Mamma's here.

46:09.767 --> 46:12.269
OK. OK.

46:12.437 --> 46:14.521
There you are. OK.

46:15.565 --> 46:18.525
- There we are.
- Thank you. Thank you, Doctor.

46:18.693 --> 46:20.735
l thought I was losing him.

46:20.903 --> 46:23.196
lt's OK. He's gonna be fine.

46:25.741 --> 46:28.994
Could you... could you
move the toys from that bed, please?

46:29.162 --> 46:32.247
Could you move the toys
from that bed, please?

46:39.464 --> 46:42.924
Whoa! Big boy.

46:43.092 --> 46:45.802
Big boy. Here we go.

46:49.515 --> 46:54.019
- OK, baby. l'm so sorry. Sorry.
- lt's OK. Don't say sorry.

46:54.187 --> 46:56.480
Don't say sorry.

46:57.440 --> 46:59.566
- So this is where you live?
- Yes.

46:59.734 --> 47:01.735
Why not stay with the other wives?

47:01.903 --> 47:06.907
Since I had Mackenzie, my husband
prefers us to be somewhere more private.

47:07.074 --> 47:09.743
This is ridiculous.

47:09.911 --> 47:15.749
l think your child has epilepsy.
lt's a perfectly treatable condition.

47:15.917 --> 47:21.087
- The president does visit you here?
- He visits the children, not me.

47:21.964 --> 47:24.799
l'm a bad omen.

47:28.221 --> 47:29.846
OK.

47:30.014 --> 47:35.268
l'm gonna make an appointment
for Mackenzie at the hospital. All right?

47:35.436 --> 47:39.981
l will tell the president
how helpful you have been.

